{{About|the 2012 documentary film|the 2015 video game|Life Is Strange}}
'''''Life Is Strange''''' is a 2012 American documentary film of interviews giving an [[oral history]] portrait of the life of pre-World War II European Jews by filmmaker Isaac Hertz. The film juxtaposes the childhood memories of interviewees with archival footage. Interviewees include Israeli president [[Shimon Peres]], author [[Uri Orlev]], academics, Nobel laureates, and friends of the filmmaker, [[Walter Kohn]], [[Robert J. Aumann]], Alain Jakubowicz, Sammy Grundwerg, Ron Samuels, Zachary Cirino, Chaim Hertz, Arianne Brown, Artem Zuev and Jean-Michel Guirao.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/30/entertainment/la-et-mn-life-is-strange-capsule-20120831 |title=Review: An oddly effective 'Life Is Strange' |date=August 30, 2012 |first=Sheri |last=Linden |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/film/holocaust-oral-histories-are-shared-in-the-shapeless-life-is-strange-6440735 |title=Holocaust Oral Histories are Shared in the Shapeless ''Life Is Strange'' |first=Chris |last=Klimek |publisher=[[The Village Voice]] |date=January 24, 2014}}</ref>

The film is 96 minutes long and explores pre-war [[Yiddish]] culture and the experience of living in a world very different from what it was like in the past.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishinstlouis.org/event/hmlc-tisha-bav-film/ |title=HMLC to Commemorate Tisha B’Av with Special Film Program |publisher=JewishinStLouis |year=2016 |accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> It has received criticism for the unclear reasoning behind the assortment of people interviewed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coveringmedia.com/movie/2012/08/life-is-strange.html |title=Life is Strange (2011/2012) |first=Anne |last=Borin |publisher=Covering Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2012/film/reviews/life-is-strange-1117948094/ |title=Review: ‘Life Is Strange’ |first=Alissa |last=Simon |publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref>

